 {"id":"bd-12o8","title":"Demo Showcase: Advanced Text Editor","description":"## Background

A serious text editor is a canonical "TUI boss fight":
- Unicode width and cursor movement
- selection, copy/paste, multi-line operations
- search/replace over large buffers
- incremental redraw without flicker

This screen exists to prove FrankenTUI can support *real* interactive editing primitives (ftui-text + widgets) with deterministic rendering, strong invariants, and performance that scales.

## UX / Demo Flow

- Main pane: multi-line editor with line numbers, selection highlights, and a visible caret.
- Secondary pane: search/replace UI (query input, match count, next/prev match).
- Status bar: cursor position (line/col), selection length, mode, and performance counters (optional).

Suggested keybindings (exact mapping can be adjusted to project conventions):
- Arrow keys / Home / End: navigation
- Shift+Arrow: selection
- Ctrl+F: focus search
- Enter: next match
- Ctrl+H: toggle replace UI
- Ctrl+Z / Ctrl+Y: undo/redo (ties into bd-1nac)

The goal is to feel "surprisingly close to a real editor" while still being a demo.

## Architecture Notes

- Data model: use ftui-text rope/editor types as the single source of truth for content.
- Rendering:
  - Use theme-aware styles from ftui-extras::theme (syntax::* and alpha::* where appropriate).
  - Avoid per-frame allocations for layout/render of large buffers.
- Search:
  - Provide a fast path for ASCII queries.
  - Ensure determinism and stable tie-breaking for match ordering.

## Acceptance Criteria

- Editor supports:
  - multi-line input + deletion
  - selection
  - search with next/prev match
  - replace (single + replace-all) with a clear confirmation step
- Rendering is deterministic under fixed inputs and terminal size.
- The UI remains usable in inline mode (no scrollback corruption).

Additionally (project-wide standards):
- Alien Artifact: define invariants + failure modes; if heuristics exist, specify an explainable decision rule (evidence ledger / Bayes factors where applicable)
- Extreme Optimization: baseline -> profile -> opportunity matrix; for each perf change include an isomorphism proof + golden output checksums
- Unit tests: happy path + edge cases + regression fixtures; add property tests for core invariants where applicable
- E2E: scripts with verbose JSONL logging (env, capabilities, timings, seed, checksums) + deterministic mode
- Visual rigor: enforce contrast bounds + deterministic rendering under fixed seeds; include snapshot fixtures and log theme IDs
- Logging: E2E logs are JSONL with stable schema (run_id, case, env, seed, timings, checksums, capabilities, outcome)

## Alien Artifact Upgrades (Concrete)

- Rope invariants (bd-12o8.7):
  - document invariants (indices, grapheme boundaries, selection ranges)
  - add property tests for round-trip edits and cursor movement
- Search/replace optimization (bd-12o8.8):
  - choose an algorithmic strategy (e.g., incremental / cached match indices)
  - prove correctness with differential tests against a slow reference implementation

## Extreme Optimization

- Define perf targets:
  - large buffer navigation remains sub-millisecond per keypress at 80x24
  - search over N lines has a defined p95 bound
